canonical_structure.name: UBX-MON-IO
canonical_structure.description: I/O system status. Reports receive/transmit byte counts and error statistics for the receiver's communication ports.

variable.description: Payload length is determined by the number of ports (N) supported by the receiver. Each port status block is 20 bytes.

fields.name: parityErrs
fields.description: Number of 100 ms timeslots with parity errors

fields.name: framingErrs
fields.description: Number of 100 ms timeslots with framing errors

fields.name: overrunErrs
fields.description: Number of 100 ms timeslots with overrun errors

fields.name: breakCond
fields.description: Number of 100 ms timeslots with break conditions

issues: The extracted fields (nPins, flags, pinMask, etc.) correspond to a hardware/PIO monitoring message (likely UBX-MON-HW or similar), not the standard UBX-MON-IO (0x0A 0x02) communication port status message.
Subsequent version HPG 1.32 (Extraction 6) uses the standard structure, confirming this is an error in Extraction 5.

adjudication.reasoning: 11 out of 12 extractions agree on a single structure: a variable-length payload consisting solely of repeated 20-byte blocks describing communication port status (RX/TX bytes, error counts). Extraction 5 is a clear outlier containing fields (nPins, flags with rtcCalib/safeBoot) that belong to a different message (likely UBX-MON-HW or UBX-MON-PIO). Since the message ID 0x0A 0x02 is consistent across all versions, and later versions of the same firmware family (HPG 1.32) return to the standard structure, Extraction 5 is adjudicated as a hallucination/extraction error where the LLM likely parsed the wrong message definition table.
